"We are attempting to address the fragility of the information space," Arweave's cofounder and CEO Sam Williams told Business Insider in an interview. The company came through Techstars' Berlin incubator, though Williams most recently was studying for a Ph.D. in computer science at the University of Kent in the UK. 

"We help people in China speak about the reality on the ground, i.e., coronavirus, without their voice being censored by the government," Williams added.

He told Business Insider that the idea for Arweave came after he read George Orwell's "1984" and studied authoritarian governments such as those in Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union.

Arweave users pay for storage on the permaweb for time spans as long as a century, and users in more than 50 countries support the platform through storage nodes worldwide.

posts.subject: PLENTY of blame to go around - but he's the one who used them up then failed to replenish.
posts.body:
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/04/03/fact-check-did-obama-administration-deplete-n-95-mask-stockpile/5114319002/


Our rating: True

We rate this claim TRUE because it is supported by our research. There is no indication that the Obama administration took significant steps to replenish the supply of N95 masks in the Strategic National Stockpile after it was depleted from repeated crises. Calls for action came from experts at the time concerned for the countrys ability to respond to future serious pandemics. Such recommendations were, for whatever reason, not heeded.


Now, do I think that Trump is any smarter here? No.

It may be years before there's enough capacity available to replenish those stockpiles. Not possible at the moment.

Something to ponder? How much in the way of emergency supplies can you purchase at the price of a single aircraft carrier?

Perhaps a better place for anger to start?

posts.subject: Things get difficult when governments lie or fail "scorekeeper" duties
posts.body:
https://chiefio.wordpress.com/2020/04/02/over-1000-dead-usa_today-26000-new-cases/

(Pretty lively discussion there)

H.R. says:	
2 April 2020 at 3:48 am	

We got home from Florida on March 5th and our Chinese-born (now American citizen) daughter-in-law finally thought it was safe enough to visit us this past Saturday, the 29th.

Shes the one who was in Wuhan in December, Shenzhen in January, and Shanghai in February and missed getting hit every time.

1) She is beyond paranoid about this virus. Im pretty sure her visit with us is the first time she has left their house since she returned from China.

2) I asked her if she believed the numbers coming from China and she just said, No. They cannot be believed.

Adding up 1 and 2, it seems that she sees the Wuhan Virus as a serious threat.

posts.subject: /williambanzai7/ This is just a sample - post will be deleted
posts.body:
in a few weeks to preserve the purity of Donald.win.

WilliamBanzai7 normally posts to Zero hedge, and I suspect he's had his problems with other hosting...especially since he likely lives iin HK. An ideal outcome for everyone would have him posting all his original work to 08chan FIRST....then to other outlets.

But I guess that depends on how many of us are willing to seed his efforts?

He doesn't know about "/williambanzai7/" yet. I hope to notify him only if it takes off and is seeded properly. Only time and a test of the fates will tell.......

Bottom line? If you hate censorship - you must support decentralized efforts. No one is gonna do it without you.

posts.subject: He's is a jerk and a bully - but never let perfection be the enemy of good
posts.body:
Would YOU want to get on his enemies list with YOUR business? Would your business be more willing to tell other presidents "No"?

"God just make that capricious asshole go away...."


(spotted today)


Cowboy logic.
Consider thiswhen the President is a jerk

Joe Herr

The bottom line has been that Trump is a jerk. Hes crude, he bloviates, he gets his feelings hurt and hes a hot head.

Let me tell you what else he is:

He is a guy that demands performance.

He is a guy that asks lots of questions. The questions he asks arent cloaked in fancy phrases, they are why the hell. questions. For decades the health industry has thrown away billions of face masks after one use. Trump asks, Why the hell are we throwing them away? Why not sterilize them and use them numerous times?

Hes the guy that gets hospital ships readied in one week, when it would have taken a bureaucrat weeks or months to get it done.

Hes the guy that gets temporary hospitals built in three days. Hes the guy that gets industries to build ventilators and face masks in a business thats highly regulated by agencies that move like sloths.

Hes the guy that asks why we arent using drugs that might work on people that are dying; what the hell do we have to lose? In spite of all the naysayers.

Hes the guy that shut down travel from China, when the liberals and the media were screaming xenophobia and racist.

Hes the guy that ran on securing the border in the face of a screaming press and media. When he shut down borders in the midst of the coronavirus virus they were up in arms over such a draconian move. Then the rest of the world followed suit all over, including the European Union between member countries.

Has he made mistakes? Yep. Everyone I know would have. All of these experts wouldnt have done any better. Trump is working harder than Ive ever seen a President work. He isnt hiding in his office, hes out front every day.

Take for instance, all the shortages of PPEs and ventilators. Im unaware of anything that prevented all of these governors from ordering all the PPE and ventilators for emergency purposes over the last two years. And yet, it is Trumps fault that they didnt.

Hes balanced his approach and listened to the experts, when his distractors said he wouldnt and couldnt.

When he offers hope, they say hes lying and when hes straight forward, he should be hopeful. Its a no win, but he is not deterred by all of that BS coming from the press and the liberals.

Ill take this kind of leadership over a nice guy that can make eloquent speeches.

And you know it's true since this came from the internet :)

But there's still much we don't know, and one of these wild stories may in fact be true.

>>8177222a-6c5f-4563-a79f-230b619e79fe
Can see problems from both sides. First, why isn't collection of such data more tightly regulated with government limits? Perhaps a gatekeeper board to oversee if it ever actually gets onto someone's "permanent record".

That said, if you were a landlord - you would certainly subscribe to such a service to protect yourself. No one wishes to be the bagholder, and no one has resources they can afford to give away. Screening renters would likely affect your bottom line more than ANYTHING else.

I see big problems ahead as this economy slips.

>>7f22bd84-3032-4529-b63c-1c4b7f95013b
Whatever is said about Antifa's people and motives - they appear to be much more competent than the white supremacist groups. At minimum, concealing identity is the only way unapproved groups can survive.

But even they fail. Put an Antifa member under enough pressure - they will crack and expose the entire organization.

Doesn't hafta be like this. But to get to a point where governments are forced to destroy their entire society just to eradicate the cancer - then groups need an upgrade both for motivation and organization.

1. A more focused objective, and one which the host population might be sympathetic to. Say preserving the Bill of Rights with real violence.

2. A method of organizing which is resistant to single point failure. Like a cellular organization.

3. Cultivation of lone wolves willing to sacrifice themselves for a cause. Objective goes out via the organization's comm channels - individual self assigns that objective then carries it out. All with an emphasis on avoiding collateral damage to innocent bystanders. McVeigh had sympathizers - but he killed babies. People are much less likely to condemn targeted assassinations than mass killings.

Setting up organizations to effectively resist government takedowns likely requires mathematicians. They would have a better handle on the probabilities. Outlining the design would be a challenging  thus attractive problem for them to solve.

Properly executed, an internal resistance group should be more than a match for anything a government could array against them. If that government is unwilling to liquidate the host population - the resistance survives. Liquidation IS the price of shutdown.....
